\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32 Atari ST\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The Atari ST was a 16bit computer of the Eighties.\par
Beside the price, its forces were a no-nonsense graphical operating system (the GEM, that also existed on the PC), a very good flicker-free monochrome display for professional use, and MIDI ports. Thanks to the latter, the Atari ST was for a while the computer of choice for musicians, running the best MIDI software available (such as Cubase and Notator, Logic Audio's ancestor). In this domain, the ST was number one. In fact it is still used in some studios.\par
Its native sound is produced by the modest YM2149 chip, which is not good at sample playback but had some good tunes composed for it and even a cool speech synthesiser. \par
The ST struggles on scrolling action games because its chipset wasn't dedicated to that sort of childish programs, it was a serious computer. The STE version is better in this respect, in other words, less serious.\par
The ST has a great collection of games nevertheless, including action games, including scrollers.\par
Unlike most computers even today, the ST featured two useful keys: Help and Undo (mapped to Page Up and Page Down in Steem!)\par
Downsides of the ST were that earlier models were sold with single-sided drives, which forced the industry to compromise, the OS in ROM couldn't be easily fixed, memory wasn't easily extendable and viral piracy readily killed the platform.\par
\par

