(Debugger only, emu detect not necessary:)\par
$ffc1f4 wipe log (Debugger)\par
$ffc123 trigger breakpoint (Debugger)\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Clock always correct\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When this option is checked, the various ways the system can get the date and time will be hacked to report the PC time (the little clock in your taskbar). So that if you stop emulation for a while, you still get the correct time when you resume, and not the emulated time. This covers the Gemdos software clock, the Mega ST Ricoh clock and the 6301 keyboard chip. This option can interfere with some programs.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Default ST configs\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 If checked, Steem looks into the current configuration folder for a configuration file with exactly the same name as the ST model which you select on the Machine page, e.g. STF.ini. You need to save such a file, the best way is to go through the Configuration page where you can select which options are to be retrieved. Maybe it's best to only select \i Machine and TOS\i0  for this purpose.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32\lang1033 Disk manager\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22\lang2057 This window controls all the disks on the ST, and the two boxes up the top hold the disks currently in the drives. This window is resizable.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Disk Images\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Disk images are floppy disks turned into files, this is how most programs are accessed on ST emulators. For details of how to create disk images from ST floppy disks have a look at the "disk image howto.txt" that comes with Steem. You will find most images on the internet however.\par
\par
The large box at the bottom of the disk manager window shows all the disk images in the current directory. The disk manager is like a little Explorer window, you can go into a folder by double clicking on it or by selecting it and pressing return. All disk image files, zip/rar/7z/bz2/gz/tar/arj archive files and any Windows shortcuts to those types of files are shown. \par
\par
Steem needs some DLL files to handle archive files.\par
-unzipd32.dll for zip files\par
-rar: unrar.dll.\par
-7z/bz2/gz/tar/arj: ArchiveAccess.dll\par
ArchiveAccess.dll manages zip and rar files too if the other plugins are not available to Steem.\par
\par
Steem doesn't know if some archive contains an image or not, so all archives are displayed in the Disk manager regardless, but maybe clicking on them is useless. It's up to you to sort your directories, of course. "Garbage in, garbage out."\par
\par
To insert a disk image into a drive, drag it to the box to the right of the big drive icon. To remove it from the drive just drag it back out to the directory view (or press Delete).\par
\par
If you right click in the directory view a menu will pop up allowing you to create a new standard size disk image (ST), a custom size disk image (ST, MSA or DIM), a STW disk image or an HFE (Rev.1.1) disk image. High density versions are available for ST and STW.\par
\par
Custom disk images can be up to 2 megabytes in size, although larger ones are emulated correctly (in fast mode), most TOS versions didn't support them, you may find they will only work with TOS 2.06 or maybe not at all. \par
\par
ST disk images contain raw data bytes without any meta information (so that emulators must guess the disk configuration, if it isn't correctly written on the disk image). MSA and DIM images also contain extra information. MSA images can be created on an ST using Magic Shadow Archiver. Steem can handle compressed images. DIM images can be created on an ST using \i FastCopy Pro\i0 . Steem needs all sectors.\par
\par
STW and HFE disk images include clock bits as well as data, encoded into MFM words. Those STW and HFE images are more than twice larger than ST images but allow emulating the WD1772 disk controller at a lower level and so handling special disk formats. Because they're formatted inside the emulated ST, there's no sides/tracks/sectors options. You get a raw disk full of random data, lucky you! It's up to you to format the disk exactly as you would on a ST. STW is the simplest such format. If you open a disk image in a hex editor, you will find sync marks coded as $4489. HFE is optimised for the HxC floppy emulator hardware. It's quite handy if you own such device. \par
\par
Important: if you plan to write on STW or HFE disk images, accurate disk access times (ADAT) mode is more reliable.\par
\par
Beside those ST, MSA, DIM, STW and HFE disk images Steem can create itself, it is also able to handle:\par
-STT images (read-only)\par
-STX images (read-only, need pasti.dll)\par
-IPF and CTR images created with Kryoflux hardware (read-only, need CAPSImg.dll)\par
-SCP images created with Supercard Pro hardware (read-only)\par
\par
A right click option allows you to convert DIM, MSA and ST images to STW. Make sure both drives are empty when you do that to avoid any interference.\par
\par
About STX, IPF and CTR images, as they are handled by a third-party plugin, whether they work or not is also up to this plugin. Make sure you have the last version.\par
\par
Steem directly handles SCP images, there's no plugin, so any bug should be fixed in Steem itself. This is the triumph of low-level emulation. All sorts of disk protections are handled just by transforming fluxes into bits using basic algorithms, without knowing anything of the protection. Those algorithms (part of the WD1772 emulation) were vaguely inspired by code in MESS and SPS (formerly CAPS) projects.\par
\par
STT is a Steem-specific format that is to be considered legacy. It is a sort of "STX light", it was abandoned when the STX format appeared.\par
\par
If you right click in the box to the right of the big drive icon, a context menu allows you to toggle the read-only property (important for some games), swap disks A and B (a keyboard shortcut can interfere with the game), remove the disk, or go to where the disk is stored. \par
\par
Right clicking on a disk image displays a menu with a myriad of options to allow you to organise and use your disk images. "Get Contents" is useful if the disk image is a compilation disk, selecting it will display a list of what the disk contains. "MSA Converter" is a great program that allows you to edit the contents of a disk and convert it to a different format. \par
"Properties" allows you to change the way Steem uses the disk, it is very unlikely you will have to change the setting from the default.\par
\par
You can also run config files (INI) from the disk manager.\par
\par
If you double click in some empty space of the main window, you go to the parent folder of the current one.\par
\par
If you don't want to use the Disk manager to select disk images, two shortcuts are available to use Windows' classic file selector instead.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Drive icons\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Left-clicking on the B: drive icon (dis)connects drive B:.\par
\par
Right-clicking on the drive icons opens a context menu with some "useful" options to:\par
Stop the motor (if it's running you crazy).\par
Change the 'SEEK' sound (if it's running you crazy). Unfortunately, this doesn\rquote t sound as good as in SainT.\par
Turn your fine SF314 double sided drive into a miserable SF354 single-sided drive (if you were unlucky back then and feel really nostalgic).\par
Select the side of the disk as if you were using a 'freeboot' switch (don't forget to reset that later!)\par
Select drive sound samples. You pick the folder, the files must have those names:\par
drive_startup.wav, drive_spin.wav, drive_click.wav, drive_seek.wav\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 GEMDOS Hard Drives\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Another handy button on the disk manager is the GEMDOS Hard Drives button. It opens the hard drive manager. You can have up to 10 virtual hard drives. To set one up select the folder on your PC and then select the letter that you want it to be on the ST. Those virtual drives are called GEMDOS drives because they're based on interception of GEMDOS commands.\par
\par
You need to know that this type of emulation is very convenient for you, because you just use your PC hard drive, but it is based on hacks, and in some cases, it could not work as on a real Atari. \par
Hard drives aren't as reliable as disk images, most things will work but not everything. If a program isn't working properly copy it to a disk image (using the ST desktop) to see if that helps. Another option in this box is to choose which hard drive to boot from if floppy drive A is empty. You can force Steem to boot from a hard drive even when drive A contains a disk by holding down the CONTROL key when you run after performing a cold reset of the ST.\par
\par
Right-clicking on this icon will toggle GEMDOS hard drives on/off.\par
\par
Notice: this emulation based on interception will only work with TOS and compatible OS as EmuTOS, not MagiC for instance. \par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 ACSI Hard Drives\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 There's also an icon for ACSI hard drives. Right-clicking on this icon will toggle ACSI hard drives on/off, left-clicking opens a box with setup details. ACSI (Atari Computer Systems Interface) was the SCSI-like interface between the ST and a hard disk or a laser printer (not emulated). ACSI emulation uses img files that contain all sectors of an Atari hard drive (data only, like an ST floppy disk image). The size limit is 1GB in Steem. Note that unlike GEMDOS hard drives, each ACSI device may be split into several partitions (C:, D:...). The driver you use must be able to handle each of those drives (Atari AHDI is fine, though some programs may prefer ICD Pro). \par
\par
Two ready examples are provided in the download, images of the familiar SH204 and MEGAFILE 60. It is also possible to enable GEMDOS virtual hard disks at the same time as ACSI virtual hard disks, you need to adapt letters of course. ACSI drives will take the first letters. It's handy to copy files. Transfer speed depends on Disk manager 'Accurate Disk Access Times' option, but even when it's not checked, the ST operates slowly compared with a (modern) PC.\par
\par
It is even possible to format those disk images inside Steem (for advanced users). More importantly, you can use a 3rd party file manager to edit ST hard disk images, 'Drive image' by Petari:\par
{{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://atari.8bitchip.info/drimus.php }}{\fldrslt{http://atari.8bitchip.info/drimus.php\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22  \par
\par
Note that some programs will work with a GEMDOS hard drive but not with an ACSI one, sometimes depending on the driver. AFAIK it's correct emulation.\par
\par
In turn, ACSI emulation being lower level, it should be compatible with any alternative OS, such as Magic.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Home Folder\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 The disk manager allows you to select a home folder. This is where all your disks or shortcuts to disks should be stored. You can go to your home folder at any time by clicking the third button from the left in the disk manager window. If you are away from your home folder you can quickly move/copy/create shortcuts to disks in your home folder by right mouse button dragging them to the home button. The button to the right of the home folder button sets the current folder as your home folder. Right clicking on the home button and the set-home button brings up menus allowing you to go to/set 10 quick-folder links.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Options\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 To the right of the set-home button is the disk manager options button, it brings up a menu with the following choices:\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Accurate Disk Access Times (Slow)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Floppy disk drives are slow, horribly tediously slow, so by default Steem does away with the waits and emulates disk access at impossibly high speed. \par
Unfortunately, some ST software uses, ahem, colourful ways of accessing the STs floppy disk controller that only work if the disk access is horribly, tediously slow. Even some contemporary demos poorly program the controller. So that is the reason for this option, but don't leave it on all the time or you will surely go insane!\par
Though the 'Drive sound' and 'Drive track info' options may make this ordeal more bearable, as you can see and hear what the drive is doing, you don't get the feeling the emulator is stuck. It's emulated the way it was.\par
The option doesn't operate with CTR, IPF, and SCP images.\par
Some disks won't load without accurate timings.\par
Speed for images run by Pasti is set in 'Pasti configuration'.\par
The option also works on ACSI hard drives (but not GEMDOS).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Count DMA transfer cycles (advanced)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 On real hardware, each time disk data is transferred to or from memory, the CPU must surrender the bus. It is correct emulation to do the same, but it can be trouble according to the floppy or hard disk emulation method (especially accelerated). This option allows you to disable the feature. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Automatic fast forward on disk access\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Sometimes disk access can be really slow, so this option makes Steem always fast forward when the ST is doing it. There are some programs that continue while accessing the disk, if you are going to use one of them then you should turn this off.\par
This feature is compatible with 'Accurate Disk Access Times', with MFM, Caps (SPS) and Pasti emulation, which means you can get both accurate and fast emulation.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Read/Write Archives (Changes Lost on Eject)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 To access disk images in archives (ZIP or RAR files) Steem extracts them to a temporary file and uses that like a normal disk image file. Unfortunately re-archiving the temporary file is very difficult, Steem can't do it. Besides, modifying an archive is questionable, maybe we just shouldn't.\par
Because of this by default all disk images in archives are treated as read-only, so they can't be changed. \par
By turning on this option you can make Steem allow writes to the temporary file, but any changes will get lost when the temporary file is deleted (the disk is ejected). \par
Some ST programs require their disk to be read/write, this option will allow you to run them without having to extract them.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Disconnect disk B\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 By default, Steem emulates an ST with an external drive attached, this is usually very useful. Unfortunately, most STs only had one drive and some programs will get confused when there are two. \par
It is usually a good idea to reset after you change this option as the ST might still think there is a drive B when really there isn't.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 MFM emulation (advanced)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Option to internally use a MFM format for ST/MSA/DIM disk images. Steem automatically converts those images to STW on insertion and back on ejection. MFM emulation hopefully is more precise. It can be slower and disk image conversion takes some time too. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Pasti options\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Pasti, by Jorge Cwik (ijor at {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://www.atari-forum.com }}{\fldrslt{http://www.atari-forum.com\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22 ), is the way to use the STX floppy disk format in Steem. This format allows emulation of original (protected) floppy disks of yore. Try to use the last version of the plugin.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s4\sb40\cf2\i\f2\fs24 Use Pasti for all floppies and ACSI (advanced)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1\fs22 This will use Pasti to run ST and MSA images, and to handle ACSI disk images. You don't need to check this option to run STX images. It's useful if some images don't work otherwise. In fact, in Steem you have three ways of running the same ST or MSA disk images: Native, as MFM and in Pasti.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s4\sb40\cf2\i\f2\fs24 Configuration\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1\fs22 It opens a dialog box managed by pasti.dll. It is recommended to set all 'speed' options to 'slow' for precise emulation, which is what you should expect of STX images.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Enable ghost disks for protected disks\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Check this option to harmlessly save high scores or game progress with CTR/IPF/STX/SCP disk images. STG files are automatically created when the game tries to save data on the disk, leaving your image file untouched. The image may be in an archive. STG files are simple and compact collections of sectors, only those that have been changed. The feature may interfere with some programs, in that case you only need to disable the option.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Run PRG and TOS files\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This enables direct support of PRG and TOS files. To run standalone PRG or TOS files, you need to set up a Z: hard drive that points to a PRG folder, preloaded with a DESKTOP.INF file and an AUTO folder. Steem will copy the file in this folder (always under the same name, so don't worry about disk waste). This should work with files inside archives. The main limitation is that it only handles single files. If the PRG needs a data file, it won't work. Also, some programs just aren't meant to work that way. In this case they should be run from a floppy or hard disk.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Automatically Insert Second Disk\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Lots of games come on two disks, if this option is on when inserting a disk into drive A Steem will look for a second disk image with a similar name and insert it into drive B. Note that even if Steem manages to insert the second disk in drive B:, the game may still require a disk swap in drive A:. Many games had only one drive in mind unfortunately. The same for demos.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Hide Broken Shortcuts\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This option hides shortcuts that point to a file that doesn't exist. If you show these shortcuts, then you can right click on them and select Fix Shortcut to allow Windows to search for the target file. You may want to check this if you have many broken shortcuts that are going to stay broken to speed up displaying of their folders.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Eject Disks When Quit\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This makes Steem eject all the disks from the drives when you quit.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Double Click Action\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This allows you to configure what happens when you double click the left mouse button on a disk image (or a shortcut to a disk image). By default, doing this will insert the disk into drive A, reset the ST and then run.\par
The same effect is assigned to the 'Enter' key.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Close Disk Manager After Insert, Reset and Run\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 If you don't like the disk manager open when you run a game, give this a go.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Hide Extension\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 By default, file name extensions are hidden.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Icon Size and Icon Spacing\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Save space with small icons, see more clearly with larger spaces.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Tools\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Next to disk manager options is the disk image management tools button, it brings up a menu with the following options.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Search Disk Image Database\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Steem uses the great disk image database created and maintained by Keili to be able to recognise disk images. Using this option you can search for a program to find out what disk images contain it. To download the disks have a look at Steem's comprehensive links in the General Info dialog.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Open Current Folder in Explorer\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Opens the folder the disk manager is looking at in Windows Explorer.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Folders Pane in Explorer\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When checked causes the folders pane to appear when you open a folder in Explorer.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Find in Current Folder\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Opens a Windows find dialog with the "Look in" directory set to the current folder, useful if you have a large number of disks in many folders and you want to find one quickly.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf4\f2\fs24 Run MSA Converter\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This loads the MSA Converter program that can be used to edit disk images. It needs to be there, of course.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32\lang1033 Command-line options\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Here are some useful command line options for Steem. The easiest way to run Steem with them is to make a shortcut to Steem.exe, right click on it and select Properties. In the text box labelled Target add the command line options on the end (after the " if there is one).\par
This is also how a frontend will launch Steem.\par
Don't add - before the options.\par
\par
 NODD, GDI - don't use DirectDraw.\par
\par
 NODS, NOSOUND - don't use DirectSound.\par
\par
 .st, .msa, .stt, .dim, .stx, .ctr, .ipf, .scp, .stw, .hfe, .zip, .rar, .7z, .stz file - load disk & go. \par
If two disks are passed, then the first will go in drive A and the second will be in drive B. Autoinsert second disk won't work.\par
\par
 .prg, .tos: same as disk but those are individual ST files. \par
\par
 .sts file - load snapshot & go.\par
\par
 .stc file - insert specified cartridge.\par
\par
 NONEW - means that if one of the above files is passed to Steem and a Steem window is already open it will be opened in the current Steem and not in a new window.\par
\par
 OPENNEW - means the opposite of NONEW, the files will always be opened in a new Steem window.\par
\par
 NOLPT - this removes the option to connect an ST port to your PC's LPT ports (that option can cause a crash on some versions of Windows).\par
\par
 NOCOM - this removes the option to connect an ST port to your PC's COM ports.\par
\par
 INI=[filename] - load [filename] instead of steem.ini.\par
\par
 TRANS=[filename] - use [filename] as translation file.\par
\par
 SOF=[freq] - stands for Sound Output Frequency. Output will be forced to [freq]Hz and all other factors will be ignored (unless setting the sound card output to [freq]Hz fails, in that case Steem will ignore this option and use its usual method of determining output frequency).\par
\par
 WINDOW - force Steem to boot in windowed mode.\par
\par
 FULLSCREEN - force Steem to boot in fullscreen mode. There's also a Startup option for that.\par
\par
 DOUBLECHECKSHORTCUTS - this makes Steem's disk manager check shortcut files more thoroughly, some people have had problems when a shortcut's target file name is in a different case to the actual file. This option makes the disk manager slower to display folders with shortcuts in them.\par
\par
 SCLICK - this option makes Steem output a click when you run and stop instead of a bump.\par
\par
 NOPCJOYSTICKS - don't look for any PC joysticks, sometimes joystick drivers do some weird things!\par
\par
 OLDPORTIO - we changed how I/O to LPT and COM ports worked in v2.4, if you are using Win9x/ME then you can use this switch if it doesn't work anymore.\par
\par
 SCREENSHOT[=path] - this tells the currently open Steem to take a screenshot. If no Steem is open, then it won't do anything.\par
\par
 ALLOWREADOPEN - this command line option makes Steem open hard drive files as read only. TOS has a bug in it that allows programs that open files for read to write to them, most versions of Windows and all versions of Linux don't allow it. Steem gets around this by opening all files as read and write. \par
This works well except in circumstances when another Windows program is accessing the same file. If you want to do that then use this command line option to open the file as read-only.\par
\par
 SCREENSHOTUSEFULLNAME - this makes Steem use the full disk name as the screenshot name, rather than just the first word.\par
\par
 NONOTIFYINIT - disable the "Steem is Initialising" box.\par
\par
 STFMBORDER - if it is not overruled by the saved options or memory snapshot, this makes Steem start as a STF.\par
\par
 NOTRACE - Steem won't create a Trace.txt file with debugging info (there is also a more convenient option in the startup page).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32\lang1033 INI file options\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Those options are inside the steem.ini file to avoid bloating the emulator interface (GUI) itself.\par
They were mostly requested for special needs.\par
\par
\b DefaultSnapshot\par
\b0 You can define a shortcut, called "Load Default Memory Snapshot", that will load the memory snapshot you specify in the [Main] part of steem.ini, for example:\par
DefaultSnapshot=[path to Steem]\\memory snapshots\\mysupergame.sts\par
\b WindowTitle\par
\b0 You can change the name that is displayed as window title and in the task bar by adding a line in the [Main] part of steem.ini, for example:\par
WindowTitle=Microsoft Excel\par
It is useful if you mean to run several specialised instances, each in its own folder.\par
Limitation: mustn't be longer than 100 characters.\par
\b MonochromeDisableBorder\par
\b0 If you add this line in the [Main] part of steem.ini:\par
MonochromeDisableBorder=1\par
Borders will be off in monochrome mode, except if you switch them on after the cold reset. You can use different configurations instead.\par
\b NoNotify\par
\b0 If you add this line in the [Main] part of steem.ini:\par
NoNotify=1\par
It does the same as argument NONOTIFYINIT.\par
\b NoIntro\par
\b0 If you add this line in the [Main] part of steem.ini:\par
NoIntro=1\par
Steem won't run its intro proposing to add a shortcut, look for a TOS file and disk images. Useful for frontends, maybe.\par
\b TrueFullScreenGui\par
\b0 By default, on the D3D builds, only the Windowed Borderless fullscreen mode can show the GUI while in fullscreen.\par
If you add this line in the [Display] part of steem.ini:\par
TrueFullScreenGui=1\par
Steem will enable the GUI option for true fullscreen too, just in case it works on older systems.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32\lang1033 Debugging info\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22\lang2057 If you check the TRACE.txt startup option, Steem saves a log with that name containing some useful information in its running directory each time it is stopped. The Debugger may save both the trace file (SSE) and a \i steem.log\i0  file (legacy). The Debugger traces in both files can be far more complete and can be chosen off a menu and the Control mask browser.\par
\par
It is even possible to read the trace file from inside Steem, in the info dialog.\par
\par
Sometimes, a fatal error happens (system exception). To help reporting, an alert box describes the error. The message is also copied into the clipboard and in the Trace file. If the bug happens in Steem itself, it's sometimes possible to track it down using this message.\par
\par
Please post good reports on the Steem forum (not at atari-forum), the key is "being reproducible".\par
